_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Lisa Kaplan|2006}}\n|education    = [[University of California, Los Angeles]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Harvard University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n}}\n\n'''Bradley James Sherman''' (born October 24, 1954) is an American politician  serving as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] since 1997. He currently represents [[California's 30th congressional district]] within the [[San Fernando Valley]], in [[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles County]] and the eastern [[Simi Hills]] in [[Ventura County, California|Ventura County]]. He previously represented the state's [[California's 24th congressional district|24th]] and [[California's 27th congressional district|27th]] congressional districts, located in Los Angeles County. He currently resides in [[Sherman Oaks, California|Sherman Oaks]].\n\n==Early life, education, and early career==\nSherman was born in [[Monterey Park, California|Monterey Park]], the son of Lane and Maurice Hyman Sherman. His parents were both of [[Russian Jewish]] descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/sherman.htm |title=1. Bradley James (\"Brad\") Sherman |publisher=Freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com |date= |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> He attended [[Mark Keppel High School]] and [[Corona del Mar High School]]. He received a B.A. in political science from [[University of California, Los Angeles]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CDIR-2009-12-01/pdf/CDIR-2009-12-01-CA-H-26.pdf |title=Data |website=www.gpo.gov |format=PDF}}</ref> in 1974 and a J.D., magna cum laude, from [[Harvard Law School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/biography/sherman.html |title=Brad Sherman |publisher=Jewish Virtual Library |date= |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> in 1979.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vote-ca.org/intro.aspx?state=ca&id=cashermanbrad |title=Brad Sherman, Candidate for United States Representative District 30, California |publisher=Vote-ca.org |date= |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> He is also a tax law specialist and [[Certified Public Accountant]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sherman.house.gov/about-brad/congressman-brad-sherman |title=Congressman Brad Sherman |publisher=house.gov |date= |accessdate=November 3, 2016}}</ref> Before joining Congress, Sherman was on staff at one of the nations\u2019 big-four [[Certified Public Accountant|CPA]] firms. While at the firm, he audited large businesses and governmental entities, provided tax law counsel on multimillion-dollar transactions, advised entrepreneurs and small businesses on tax and investment issues, and helped represent the Government of the Philippines under President Aquino in a successful effort to seize assets of deposed President Marcos.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/arena/bio/brad_sherman.html |title=Arena Profile: Brad Sherman |publisher=Politico |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> Sherman was also an instructor at Harvard Law School\u2019s International Tax Program.<ref name=\"house1\"/>\n\n===Board of Equalization (1991\u20131996)===\nSherman\u2019s public service career includes serving on the [[State Board of Equalization (California)|California State Board of Equalization]] from 1991 to 1996. He was Chairman of the Board from 1991 to 1995.<ref name=\"house1\">{{cite web|url=http://bradsherman.house.gov/about/biography.shtml |title=Biography &#124; Congressman Brad Sherman, Representing the 27th District of California |publisher=Bradsherman.house.gov |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported that the campaign for the Board of Equalization involved numerous attacks. Claude Parrish, Sherman's opponent, said that an attorney general candidate declined to endorse Sherman due to a post on the state's elected tax appeals board. Sherman replied, calling it \"one of the most outrageous hit pieces in contemporary California political history.\"<ref name=\"Potholders to Brickbats\">{{cite news|last=Feldman|first=Paul|title=STATE BOARD OF EQUALIZATION : Sherman-Parrish Race Goes From Potholders to Brickbats|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-11-03/news/mn-3226_1_state-board-of-equalization|accessdate=29 August 2012|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=3 November 1990}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives (1997\u2013present)==\n\n===Elections===\nIn 1994, incumbent Democratic U.S. Congressman [[Anthony C. Beilenson]] of [[California's 24th congressional district]] barely survived the [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1994|Republican Revolution]], winning re-election by just a two-point margin,<ref name=\"ourcampaigns.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=518485 |title=CA District 24 \u2013 D Primary Race |publisher=Our Campaigns |date=March 26, 1996 |accessdate=2012-09-10}}</ref> by far the worst election performance of his career. In 1996, Beilenson decided to retire.\n\nSherman decided to run and won the 7-candidate Democratic primary with 54% of the vote.<ref name=\"ourcampaigns.com\"/> In the general election, he defeated Republican nominee Rich Sybert (also 1994 nominee) 49%\u201344%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=29376 |title=CA District 24 Race \u2013 Nov 05, 1996 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-09-10}}</ref> However, he has never faced another contest nearly that close.\n\nIn 1998, he won re-election with 57% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=30306 |title=CA District 24 Race \u2013 Nov 03, 1998 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-09-10}}</ref> After that, he has won re-election every two years with at least 62%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=746 |title=Candidate \u2013 Brad Sherman |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-09-10}}</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{see also|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2012#District 30}}\nRedistricting following the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]] drew the homes of Sherman and fellow Democrat [[Howard Berman]], who had previously represented the 28th District, into the 30th District.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=740837 |title=CA \u2013 District 30 \u2013 Open Primary Race \u2013 Jun 05, 2012 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/berman_v_sherman/item/introducing_the_berman_v_sherman_blog_20110915/|title=Introducing the Berman v. Sherman blog|date=September 15, 2011|first=Jonah|last=Lowenfeld|newspaper=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles]]}}</ref> The redrawn 30th was more Sherman's district than Berman's; Sherman retained approximately 60% of his former territory, while Berman retained 20% of his former voters.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/09/us/politics/lines-redrawn-longtime-allies-fight-for-a-seat.html?pagewanted=all |work=NY Times|title=Lines Redrawn, Longtime Allies Fight for a Seat |first=Jennifer|last=Steinhauer |date=December 8, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2012/06/clone-wars/308983/ |work=The Atlantic |title=Clone Wars}}</ref> On June 5, 2012, Sherman faced Berman in the primary for California\u2019s new 30th Congressional district. Sherman finished first, leading 42% to 32%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2012/06/rep-sherman-tops-rep-berman-in-calif-dem-primary/|work= ABC News|title= Rep. Sherman Tops Rep. Berman in Calif. Dem Primary}}</ref> However, due to the new election system in California, which put the two candidates who received the most votes in the primary against each other regardless of party, the two congressmen again faced each other in the general election.<ref name=\"New Election System\">{{cite news|last=Slosson|first=Mary|title=Democrats face Democrats in new California election system|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/06/07/us-usa-campaign-primaries-idUSBRE85602U20120607|accessdate=12 June 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=6 June 2012}}</ref> Neither candidate received an official endorsement from the state Democratic Party.<ref name=\"No endorsement\">{{cite news|title=No state Democratic Party endorsement for Berman or Sherman.|url=http://www.dailynews.com/news/ci_21086471/no-state-democratic-party-endorsement-berman-or-sherman|accessdate=23 July 2012|newspaper=Daily News|date=16 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nBerman was the establishment candidate. He was endorsed by over 20 congressmen, including party leaders [[Steny Hoyer]] and [[Xavier Becerra]]. In addition, he was endorsed by sitting [[Governor of California|Governor]] [[Jerry Brown]], sitting [[Los Angeles]] [[Mayor of Los Angeles|Mayor]] [[Antonio Villaraigosa]], and the state's two U.S. Senators: [[Barbara Boxer]] and [[Dianne Feinstein]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2012/06/06/sherman-and-berman-brawl-in-california-house-race-to-continue-through-fall/ |work=Fox News |title=Sherman and Berman brawl in California House race to continue through fall |date=June 6, 2012}}</ref> He was also endorsed by ten Republican congressmen from California: [[David Dreier]], [[Wally Herger]], [[Dan Lungren]], [[Elton Gallegly]], [[Buck McKeon]], [[Ed Royce]], [[Jerry Lewis]], [[Ken Calvert]], [[Mary Bono Mack]], and [[Darrell Issa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/california-howard-berman-endorsed-by-10-gop-members|title=California: Howard Berman Endorsed by 10 GOP Members|date=11 October 2012|website=Roll Call|accessdate=13 July 2017}}</ref> In addition, he was endorsed by two Republican U.S. Senators: [[John McCain]] (R-AZ), [[Lindsey Graham]] (R-SC), and by Independent U.S. Senator [[Joe Lieberman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/263853-hoyer-endorses-rep-berman-over-rep-sherman#ixzz2ssBvnTMB|title=Hoyer endorses Rep. Berman over Rep. Sherman|first=Emily|last=Goodin|date=24 October 2012|publisher=|accessdate=13 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Strange Bedfellows\">{{cite news|last=VARA|first=VAUHINI|title=California Races Form Strange Bedfellows |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390444130304577560083567532406?mod=googlenews_wsj#|accessdate=4 September 2012|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=10 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nSherman was endorsed by [[Lieutenant Governor of California|Lieutenant Governor]] [[Gavin Newsom]], former President [[Bill Clinton]], and former [[Massachusetts Governor]] [[Michael Dukakis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calbuzz.com/2012/01/berman-v-sherman-politics-v-politics-in-cd-30/|title=Berman v. Sherman: Politics v. politics in CD 30|publisher=|accessdate=13 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the general election, Sherman defeated Berman, 60%\u201340%.<ref name = \"Brad Sherman defeats Howard Berman\">{{cite news |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2012/11/07/brad-sherman-defeats-howard-berman-for-30th-congressional-seat/ |title=Brad Sherman Defeats Howard Berman For 30th Congressional Seat |accessdate=7 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n*\n\n===Tenure=== <!--- Courtesy note. [[Sherman Amendment]] links here -->\nFirst elected to the [[United States House of Representatives]] in 1996, Sherman is serving his tenth term in Congress. He is a senior member of the House Foreign Affairs Committee, and serves as the top Democrat on the Subcommitee on Asia. He is the Chairman Emeritus of the Subcommittee on International Terrorism, Nonproliferation and Trade. He is also a senior member of the Financial Services Committee.<ref name=\"house1\"/>\n\nSherman has held over 160 Town Hall meetings since being elected to Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.com/ci_20332314/brad-sherman-states-his-case?source=most_emailed |title=Rep. Brad Sherman: I'm the humble candidate |publisher=LA Daily News |date=April 6, 2012 |accessdate=2012-09-10}}</ref> In the [[Washingtonian (magazine)|''Washingtonian'']]'s 2012 anonymous survey of congressional staff, Sherman was named the second meanest member of the House, finishing only behind [[Sheila Jackson Lee]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Best and Worst of Congress 2012|url=https://www.washingtonian.com/2012/08/29/best-and-worst-of-congress-2012/|website=Washingtonian|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Environment====\nSherman has earned a 100% rating from the [[Sierra Club]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sierraclub.org/planet/200011/endorsements.asp |title=Endorsements \u2013 Planet Newsletter |publisher=Sierra Club |date=November 2000 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> and the [[League of Conservation Voters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://capwiz.com/lcv/bio/keyvotes/?id=625&congress=1121&lvl=C |title=Representative Brad Sherman (D-CA 27th) |publisher=League of Conservation Voters |date= |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nServing on the House Budget Committee in 1997, Sherman authored the Sherman Amendment to the Budget Resolution, providing an additional $700 million for the acquisition of environmentally important lands in FY \u201898.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997/sep/04/local/me-28798 | work=Los Angeles Times | title=Fund Intended for Parkland | date=September 4, 1997}}</ref>\n\n====Labor====\nSherman\u2019s voting record has most often earned him a 100% rating from the [[AFL-CIO]], the Service Employees International Union ([[SEIU]]), and the American Federation of State, County & Municipal Employees ([[AFSCME]]).<ref name=\"The Hill Ratings\">{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/resources/lawmaker-ratings/82965-rep-brad-sherman-d-calif |title=Rep. Brad Sherman (D-Calif., 27th) |publisher=The Hill |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Vote Smart Ratings\">{{cite web|url=https://www.votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/142/brad-sherman |title=Brad Sherman \u2013 Interest Group Ratings |publisher=Project Vote Smart |date= |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSherman was an original co-sponsor of [[The Employee Free Choice Act]] when it was introduced at the start of 2007, and again when it was re-introduced in 2009.<ref name=\"Gov Track\">{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/109/hr1696 |title=Employee Free Choice Act (2005; 109th Congress H.R. 1696) |publisher=GovTrack.us |date= |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSherman introduced legislation, in 2008 and 2010, to eliminate so-called state \"[[Right to Work]]\" laws nationwide.,<ref name=\"Labor Relations\">{{cite web|first=Seth |last=Borden |url=http://www.laborrelationstoday.com/2010/10/articles/legislation/california-congressman-introduces-bill-to-repeal-right-to-work-laws/ |title=California Congressman Introduces Bill to Repeal \"Right to Work\" Laws |publisher=Labor Relations Today |date=October 5, 2010 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> and he supports a single national standard that protects labor rights. Sherman has also opposed Free Trade deals with South Korea, Colombia, and other countries, because he believes they are bad for American workers.<ref name=\"Brad Sherman\">{{cite web|author=|url=http://bradsherman.house.gov/2011/10/sherman-opposing-so-called-free-trade-agreements.shtml |title=Sherman Opposing So-Called \"Free Trade Agreements\" |publisher=Bradsherman.house.gov |date=October 27, 2011 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"You Tube\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=me4gVwCrBs4 |title=Congressman Brad Sherman Urges Rejection of U.S.-Korea Free Trade Agreement |publisher=YouTube |date=March 11, 2010 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Congressman Sherman discussing healthcare to union workers.jpg|thumb|Congressman Brad Sherman joins with members of United Food and Commercial Workers (UFCW) at a local supermarket in Sherman Oaks]]\n\n====Transportation====\nSherman has worked to reduce airport noise in the [[San Fernando Valley]]. Sherman joined several colleagues in introducing legislation, the Valley-Wide Noise Relief Act, to allow the operator of [[Bob Hope Airport]] to implement a mandatory nighttime curfew.<ref name=\"Daily News\">{{cite web|author=Adam B. Schiff, Brad Sherman and Howard Berman |url=http://www.dailynews.com/opinions/ci_17727444 |title=Support Noise Relief Act at Valley airports |publisher=LA Daily News |date=March 29, 2011 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSherman secured federal funds to initiate several improvements at the 101/405 interchange.<ref name=\"Vote Smart 405\">{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/public-statement/235437/sherman-presses-for-405-freeway-carpool-lane |title=Sherman Presses for 405 Freeway Carpool Lane |publisher=Project Vote Smart |date=February 20, 2007 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Animal rights====\nSherman\u2019s voting record has consistently earned him a 100% rating from the [[Humane Society]], which has awarded him the \u201cHumane Champion\u201d award for five consecutive years.<ref name=\"Vote Smart Ratings\" /><ref name=\"Humane Society\">{{cite web|url=http://hslf.typepad.com/political_animal/2012/01/hot-off-the-press-112th-congress-midterm-humane-scorecard.html |title=Michael Markarian: Animals & Politics: Hot Off the Press: 112th Congress Midterm Humane Scorecard |publisher=Hslf.typepad.com |date=2012-01-13 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Fiscal Policy====\nCongressman Sherman \"led the House revolt\" against the original $700 billion bailout plan, known as the [[Troubled Asset Relief Program]] (TARP).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/sleuth/2008/10/rep_sherman_not_so_popular_on.html |title=Rep. Sherman, Not So Popular On the Playground |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |first=Mary Ann |last=Akers |date=October 2, 2008}}</ref> Sherman introduced the \"Too Big to Fail, Too Big to Exist Act\", with regard to large financial entities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/hr4963 |title=H.R. 4963: Too Big to Fail, Too Big to Exist Act |publisher=[[GovTrack]] |accessdate=August 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Financial crisis====\nDuring the debate over the [[Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008]], (commonly referred to as \"the bailout of the U.S. financial system\"), Sherman was an early and outspoken critic of the proposal, leading the House revolt against the bailout bill, a move which made him \"spectacularly unpopular with both the Republican and Democratic leaderships, not to mention K Street\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/sleuth/2008/10/rep_sherman_not_so_popular_on.html | work=The Washington Post | title=Rep. Sherman, Not So Popular On the Playground}}</ref> Sherman argued that Bush and his advisors had created a panic atmosphere in an effort to get lawmakers to rubber-stamp the bill.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,425663,00.html | title = Paulson Urges Quick Action on $700 Billion Bailout Plan | last= Pergram, Associated Press | first = Chad | publisher = Fox News | accessdate = 2011-07-09 | date=September 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\n====Social Security and health care====\nSherman has said he is \"opposed to creating a voucher system for Medicare\". He wants to avoid \"turn[ing] Social Security into a welfare program\", instead keeping it \"for people who contribute to it\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynews.com/ci_15935396 |title=Representative Brad Sherman speaks to residents |newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News |last=Bartholomew |first=Dana |date=August 29, 2010}}</ref>\n\nFor his voting record and efforts in Congress, Sherman has consistently earned a 100% rating from the ''National Committee to Preserve Social Security and Medicare'', and from the AARP (American Association of Retired Persons).<ref name=\"Vote Smart Ratings\" /> Sherman supported the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]].\n\nSherman helped secure funds to develop a new women and children's patient wing at El Proyecto del Barrio\u2019s Family Health Care Clinic in Winnetka.<ref name=\"Wing patients\">{{cite news|title=health center opens wing patients|url=http://www.dailynews.com/breakingnews/ci_21313879/winnetka-family-health-center-opens-wing-patients|accessdate=24 August 2012|newspaper=The Daily News}}</ref>\n\n====Housing====\nSherman introduced the Preserving Equal Access to Mortgage Finance Programs Act (HR 1754), which raises the conforming loan limit for [[FHA loan]]s in high-cost areas such as Sherman's district.<ref name=\"Real Estate News\">{{cite web|first=Tara |last=Steele |url=http://agbeat.com/real-estate-news-events/bipartisan-congressional-efforts-restore-higher-fha-loan-limits/ |title=Bipartisan Congressional efforts restore higher FHA loan limits |publisher=AGBeat |date=November 16, 2011 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lazo |first=Alejandro |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/nov/19/business/la-fi-fha-limits-20111119 |title=Higher FHA loan limits reinstated for high-cost housing markets |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=November 19, 2011 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSherman frequently holds seminars for Valley residents in his district to address issues of home purchasing, home refinancing, and foreclosure avoidance.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sherman|first=Brad|title=Congressman Sherman On His Record Of San Fernando Valley Outreach|url=http://www.vannuysnewspress.com/2012/07/17/congressman-sherman-on-his-record-of-san-fernando-valley-outreach/|newspaper=Van Nuys News Press|date=July 17, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Congressman Brad Sherman Hosts Housing Seminar|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uylfFprGGTY|work=KNBC|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=September 10, 2012|date=February 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Civil liberties====\nSherman's legislative record received a 100% rating from the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU) in 2011, a 100% from the [[National Organization for Women]] (NOW) in 2007\u20132008, a 100% from the [[Human Rights Campaign]] in 2009\u20132010, and a 98% rating from the [[NAACP]] in 2009\u20132010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/142/brad-sherman |title=Representative Brad J. Sherman's Special Interest Group Ratings |publisher=Project Vote Smart |accessdate=August 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSherman co-sponsored the Due Process Guarantee Act,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/hr3702 |title=H.R. 3702: Due Process Guarantee Act of 2011 |publisher=[[GovTrack]] |accessdate=August 12, 2012}}</ref> which amends the Non-Detention Act of 1971 to provide that a Congressional authorization for the use of military force does not authorize the indefinite detention \u2013 without charge or trial \u2013 of U.S. citizens.\n\nIn 2011, Sherman voted against the re-authorization of the Patriot Act<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/Profiles/House/California/Brad_Sherman/Views/Homeland_Security/ |title=Brad Sherman on Homeland Security |publisher=The Political Guide |accessdate=August 12, 2012}}</ref> because of concerns that it would infringe on certain civil liberties, including the \"library provision\" that allows the FBI to acquire records about what books a person checks out from the library.\n\n====Foreign relations====\nIn August 2010, Sherman introduced legislation aimed at rescinding China's [[Most Favored Nation]] status as long as there was not \"a more level playing field between our two nations\".<ref name=Hill /> He said that \"the U.S.-China trade relationship is horrendously lopsided\".<ref name=Hill>{{cite news |url=http://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/112967-dems-ready-to-push-china-on-currency-manipulation |title=Dems ready to push China this fall |last= Stiles |first=Andrew |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |accessdate=2011-07-09}}</ref>\n\nSherman has introduced or co-sponsored more than 20 bills in the 111th and 112th Congresses that he says, \"enact tougher sanctions to isolate Iran economically and diplomatically\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/157729-house-ponders-new-sanctions-against-iran-syria|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|title=House ponders new sanctions against Iran, Syria|work=The Hill|accessdate=2012-05-15}}</ref>  His efforts have included legislation designed to close loopholes for U.S. companies with subsidiaries operating in [[Iran]], and to curtail U.S. funding of international organizations providing loans to Iran.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704789404575524050147296646?mod=WSJEUROPE_hpp_sections_world|last=Solomon|first=Jay|title=U.S. Slams Firms Over Ties to Iran|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=2012-05-15|date=October 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSherman has been a strong supporter and advocate of the [[U.S.-Israel relations|U.S-Israel relationship]], consistently supporting aid to [[Israel]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.njdc.org/site/page/brad_sherman |title=Jewish Members of Congress: Brad Sherman (Representative, California) |publisher=National Jewish Democratic Council |date= |accessdate=May 3, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120412012703/http://www.njdc.org/site/page/brad_sherman |archivedate=April 12, 2012 |df= }}</ref> In 2004, Brad Sherman first introduced the U.S.-Israel Energy Cooperation Act.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/BILLS-108hr5342ih/pdf/BILLS-108hr5342ih.pdf |title=Bills info |website=www.gpo.gov |format=PDF}}</ref> It provides grant money to joint ventures between American and Israeli academics and private sector companies that conduct research and develop energy-efficient and [[renewable energy]] technologies.\n\nOn July 9, 2014, Sherman appeared as a guest commentator on the [[Al Jazeera America]]\u2019s network. During his appearance, Sherman went after the [[Qatar]]-based owners of Al Jazeera, criticizing the owners for funding [[Hamas]]. Sherman said, \"Every one of those rockets [fired by Hamas into Israeli cities] is a war crime, almost every one. Of course it's a war crime committed by Hamas. And of course the owners of this TV network help fund Hamas.\" Sherman emphasized that Hamas often aims attacks at civilian targets.<ref>{{cite web|last1=John|first1=Rossomando|title=Democratic Congressman Calls Out Qatar's Hamas Support on Al-Jazeera America|url=http://www.investigativeproject.org/4467/democratic-congressman-calls-out-qatar-hamas#|website=The Investigative Project on Terrorism|accessdate=6 July 2015|date=18 July 2014}}</ref>  The owners of Al Jazeera that Sherman mentioned is the government of Qatar.<ref>{{cite web|title=On Al Jazeera, Congressman Calls Out Network\u2019s Qatari Owners for Funding Hamas War Crimes|url=http://www.thetower.org/0743-on-al-jazeera-congressman-calls-stations-support-of-hamas-a-war-crime/|website=TheTower.org|publisher=The Tower Magazine|accessdate=6 July 2015|date=21 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, Sherman and Congressman [[Pete Roskam]] (R-IL) requested new [[Economic sanctions|sanctions]] on Qatar in a letter to Secretary of Treasury [[Jack Lew]]. They also asked for a detailed accounting of public and private financing from within Qatar for Hamas, [[Al-Qaeda]], the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]], and the [[al-Nusra Front]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dettmer|first1=Jamie|title=U.S. Ally Qatar Shelters Jihadi Moneymen|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/12/10/rich-little-qatar-big-ugly-ties-to-terror.html|accessdate=6 July 2015|work=The Daily Beast|date=10 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nSherman and other pro-Israel members of Congress have introduced legislation to allow Israel to be part of the [[visa waiver program]].<ref>Anne Gearan, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/lawmakers-pushing-to-add-israel-to-visa-waiver-program/2014/04/26/4c99f2d8-ccbf-11e3-93eb-6c0037dde2ad_story.html Lawmakers pushing to add Israel to visa-waiver program], ''Washington Post'' (April 26, 2014).</ref><ref name=\"JTA\">[https://www.haaretz.com/israel-stymies-u-s-visa-waiver-bill-1.5238044 U.S. Visa Waiver Bill Stymied Over Arab Americans Entering Israel], Jewish Telegraphic Agency (April 13, 2013).</ref> The legislation failed because the Israeli government was unwilling to grant reciprocal visa-free travel for all U.S. citizens.<ref name=\"JTA\"/>\n\nAs a senior member of the House Committee on Foreign Affairs, Sherman has focused on Congressional recognition of the [[Armenian Genocide]], as well as increasing funding to Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_CE1pcWy55M |title=Congressman Sherman (D-CA) Statement on Armenian Genocide Resolution}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.anca.org/press_releases/press_releases.php?prid=1824 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100309200804/http://www.anca.org/press_releases/press_releases.php?prid=1824 | dead-url=yes | archive-date=2010-03-09 | title=Rep. Brad Sherman Joines with Community Activists to Rally Support for Armenian Genocide Resolution as Committee Vote Approaches | work=Armenian National Committee }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.armenianweekly.com/2012/03/22/more-than-30-reps-press-for-pro-armenia-aid-provisions/ |title=More than 30 Reps Press for Pro-Armenia Aid Provisions}}</ref>\n\n====Religion====\nSherman and his wife, who are [[Jewish]], have been members of [[Valley Beth Shalom]] \u2013 a conservative synagogue in [[Encino, California]] \u2013 for many years.\n\nIn his role as a congressman, Sherman has appeared at events sponsored by virtually every religious denomination practiced in America \u2013 including Orthodox Jewish,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.crownheights.info/index.php?itemid=6275 |title=Shliach \"Rabbi Mordy\" with Rep. Brad Sherman |accessdate=August 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chabadofthevalley.com/templates/photogallery_cdo/aid/1228444 |title=Banquet \u2013 Gala 2010 |publisher=Chabad of the Valley |date=June 3, 2010}}</ref> Reform Jewish, Conservative Jewish, Reconstructionist Jewish, Traditional Persian Jewish,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.jta.org/news/article/2007/02/20/100045/persiancandidates |title=Persian Jews politicking on Rodeo Drive |publisher=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]] |first=Karmel |last=Melamed |date=February 20, 2007}}</ref> Sephardic Jewish, the Church of Scientology,<ref name=Nots>[http://voices.washingtonpost.com/reliable-source/2009/11/rs-scientology4.html The news on the street], ''[[The Washington Post]]'' (Nov. 4, 2009)</ref><ref name=\"clabaugh\">{{cite news| last = Clabaugh  | first = Jeff | title = Church of Scientology opens new D.C. home | work = Washington Business Journal | publisher = American City Business Journals, Inc.  | date =November 9, 2009  | url = http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/stories/2009/11/09/daily9.html | accessdate = 2010-04-19 }}</ref> Muslim, Catholic,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.catholiccharitiesla.org/images/files/the_sage_newsletter/2011/may-2011-newsletter.pdf |title=Re-Dedication Marks Guadalupe Community Center\u2019s 60 Years of Service |publisher=Catholic Charities of Los Angeles |date=May 2011}}</ref> Roman Catholic, Coptic Christian, The Assyrian Church, Greek Orthodox, the Armenian Church,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.armenianchurchwd.com/primate-attends-mds-35th-anniversary-banquet-mds-principal-hagop-hagopian-honored/ |title=Primate Attends MDS 35th Anniversary Banquet \u2013 MDS Principal Hagop Hagopian Honored |accessdate=August 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.armenianchurchwd.com/palm-sunday-service-st-peter-van-nuys/ |title=Palm Sunday Service \u2013 St. Peter, Van Nuys |publisher=Western Diocese of the Armenian Church |date=March 31, 2010}}</ref> Sikh,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sikhcouncilusa.org/article.aspx?article=evtcapitolhill07 |title=Political Leaders in DC welcome Sikhs at the Capitol Hill |publisher=Sikh Council on Religion and Education |date=May 17, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/apr/17/local/me-sikhs17 |title=Southland's Sikhs Converge on a Special Day |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=April 17, 2006 |first=David |last=Haldane}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/shermanca27/4100251135/ |title=Congressman Sherman Greets Southland Sikhs on Baisakhi Day |publisher=Brad Sherman |accessdate=August 13, 2012}}</ref> Buddhism, Hindu, Russian Orthodox, the Hungarian reformed Orthodox Church, Episcopalian, Methodist, Presbyterian, the Church of Christ, non-denominational Christian, and evangelical Christian.\n\nSherman expressed condolences to the Sikh community following the deadly shootings at a Sikh temple in August 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scpr.org/news/2012/08/07/33694/wisconsin-shooting-southland-sikh-community-holds-/ |title=Wisconsin shooting: Southland Sikh community holds prayer service honoring victims |publisher=[[KPCC]] |date=August 7, 2012| last=Slater |first=Grant}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://bradsherman.house.gov/2012/08/congressman-sherman-reacts-to-shooting-at-sikh-temple-in-wisconsin.shtml |title=Congressman Sherman Reacts to Shooting at Sikh Temple in Wisconsin |publisher=Brad Sherman |date=August 6, 2012 |accessdate=7 August 2013}}</ref> After the September 11th terrorist attacks, Sherman joined with colleagues in introducing a resolution to condemn bigotry and violence against Sikh-Americans.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.anti-semitism.net/hate-crimes-2/violence-against-sikh-americans-risen-post-911.php |title=Violence against Sikh Americans risen post 9/11 |publisher=Exposing & Fighting Against Global Anti-Semitism & Anti-Jewish Racism |accessdate=August 13, 2012}}</ref> Sherman has advocated on behalf of religious minorities outside the United States, including Hindus of Pakistan and Christians and Jews in the Arab world.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://iran.bahai.us/2012/07/24/capitol-hill-event-raises-awareness-of-religious-minorities-in-the-middle-east/ |title=Capitol Hill event raises awareness of religious minorities in the Middle East |publisher=Persecution of Bah\u00e1'\u00eds in Iran |date=July 24, 2012}}</ref> Sherman introduced the Religious Minorities in the Arab World Resolution, which calls for the protection of the rights and freedoms of ethno-religious minorities, particularly in Egypt and Iraq.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/hres732/text |title=H.Res. 732: Calling for the protection of the rights and freedoms of religious minorities in the Arab world |publisher=[[GovTrack]] |accessdate=August 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Internet policy====\nIn 2011, Sherman co-sponsored [[SOPA]].<ref name=\"govtrack\">[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h112-3261 Bill H.R.3261]; GovTrack.us;</ref> Sherman\u2019s 2012 opponent [[Howard Berman]] in California\u2019s new 30th congressional district was the original co-sponsor of the SOPA legislation.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gruenwald|first=Juliana|title=As Hollywood Watches, SOPA Champion Berman Fights for His Seat|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress/as-hollywood-watches-sopa-champion-berman-fights-for-his-seat-20120407|newspaper=National Journal|date=April 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Cryptocurrency====\n\nOn March 14, 2018, Sherman made highly critical remarks about [[Bitcoin]], [[cryptocurrency]], and [[Initial Coin Offering]]s. He started his prepared remarks by saying \"Cryptocurrencies are a crock\". He further said, on Congressional record, that all Bitcoin does is allow \"a few dozen men in my district to sit in their pyjamas on their couch all day, and tell their wives they are going to be millionaires\". He further suggested that Bitcoin doesn't provide any value to the real economy, asking \"when you buy a Bitcoin, are you helping build a new factory?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?442556-1/hearing-focuses-cryptocurrency-markets|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref> On 18 July 2018, Sheman called for a ban on the dealing in or mining of cryptocurrencies by U.S. Persons; and states use of crypto currencies as a medium of exchange is useful only to individuals facilitating narcotics trafficking, terrorism, and tax evasion.<ref>https://www.c-span.org/video/?448611-1/house-panel-examines-digital-currency&start=539\n* https://www.c-span.org/video/?448611-1/house-panel-examines-digital-currency&start=3120\n</ref>\n\n====LGBT====\nSherman is a strong supporter of [[LGBT rights in the United States|LGBT rights]]. He earned a 100% rating from the [[Human Rights Campaign]], the nation's largest LGBT rights group, in the [[114th Congress|114th]], [[113th Congress|113th]], and [[112th Congress]]es.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://assets2.hrc.org/files/assets/resources/114thCongressionalScorecard.pdf|title=Congressional Scorecard: Measuring Support for Equality in the114th Congress|page=13|publisher=Human Rights Campaign|format=PDF}}</ref> \n\nSherman is a member of the [[LGBT Equality Caucus]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://lgbt-polis.house.gov/members|title=Members|publisher=LGBT Equality Caucus |accessdate=August 4, 2018}}</ref> and a supporter of [[Same-sex marriage in the United States|same-sex marriage]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Mark |last=Kellam |url=http://articles.glendalenewspress.com/2012-02-11/news/tn-gnp-0212-schiff-sherman-back-gay-marriage_1_marriage-rights-civil-rights-michael-portantino |title=Schiff, Sherman back gay marriage |publisher=Glendale News-Press |date=February 11, 2012 |accessdate=2012-09-10}}</ref> He voted in favor of the [[Don't Ask, Don't Tell Repeal Act of 2010]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2010/roll638.xml|publisher=Office of the Clerk of the United States House of Representatives|date=December 15, 2010|title=Final Results for Roll Call 638, H.R. 296}}</ref>\n\nSherman was an original co-sponsor of Congressman [[Jared Polis]]'s [[Student Non-Discrimination Act]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://polis.house.gov/UploadedFiles/1-27_SNDA_Fact_Sheet.pdf |title=Fact sheet |website=polis.house.gov |format=PDF}} </ref> Sherman is also a co-sponsor of the [[Employment Non-Discrimination Act]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/110/hr2015 |title=Employment Non-Discrimination Act of 2007 (2007; 110th Congress H.R. 2015) |publisher=GovTrack.us |date= |accessdate=2012-09-10}}</ref> In 2009, Sherman voted for the [[Matthew Shepard and James Byrd, Jr. Hate Crimes Prevention Act]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/CA/Brad_Sherman_Crime.htm |title=Brad Sherman on Crime |publisher=Ontheissues.org |date= |accessdate=2012-09-10}}</ref> which imposes additional federal penalties for crimes motivated by hatred on the basis of race, religion, or actual or perceived sexual orientation.\n\n====Abortion====\nSherman is [[pro-choice]]. He has earned a 100% rating from [[NARAL]] and [[Planned Parenthood]].<ref>[http://www.prochoiceamerica.org/government-and-you/us-government/congressional-records/california.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707112412/http://www.prochoiceamerica.org/government-and-you/us-government/congressional-records/california.html |date=July 7, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.plannedparenthoodaction.org/elections-politics/2010-elections-map.htm#/california/ush10849 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020202216/http://www.plannedparenthoodaction.org/elections-politics/2010-elections-map.htm#/california/ush10849 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=October 20, 2011 |title=Planned Parenthood Action Center |publisher=Plannedparenthoodaction.org |date= |accessdate=May 3, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n====Gun control====\nSherman has worked to [[FN 5.7\u00d728mm#Controversy|expand the definition of armor-piercing ammunition]] in US law. He was a sponsor of the Protect Law Enforcement Armor (PLEA) Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/search/pagedetails.action;jsessionid=XxQQTLHVdPYqqh16QsyX4GWgZWZ9wkfYqtCvT7q3T2G8QcCt9c5j!-961268343!234411547?sr=733&originalSearch=&st=sale&ps=10&na=&se=&sb=re&timeFrame=&dateBrowse=&collection=&historical=false&granuleId=&packageId=BILLS-110hr1784ih |title=H.R. 1784 (ih) \u2013 Protect Law Enforcement Armor Act |publisher=Gpo.gov |date= |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> Sherman has received a 100% rating from The [[Brady Campaign to Prevent Gun Violence]].<ref name=\"The Hill Ratings\"/>\n\n====International trade====\nSherman has opposed the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] (NAFTA) and the [[Central American Free Trade Agreement]] (CAFTA), arguing that the agreements cost American jobs, fail to protect foreign workers, harm the environment, and cost U.S. taxpayers billions of dollars.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://bradsherman.house.gov/2005/07/pr-tradetreaty.html.shtml |title=Trade Treaty Hurts U.S. And Central American Workers |publisher=Bradsherman.house.gov |date=July 26, 2005 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> \nSherman has also opposed a Free Trade Agreement with South Korea, arguing that a proposed U.S. trade agreement could undermine U.S. security and economic interests by benefiting China and North Korea.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/mar/16/opinion/la-oe-sherman-koreapact-20110316 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Brad | last=Sherman | title=Help South Korea, not the North | date=March 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Education====\nSherman has earned a 100% rating from the [[California Teachers Association]],{{Citation needed|date=May 2012}} the National Education Association,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ontheissues.org/CA/Brad_Sherman_Education.htm |title=Brad Sherman on Education}}</ref> and the American Federation of Teachers.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.aft.org/votes |title=The 111th Congress Voting Record |work=AFT}}</ref>\n\n====Office environment and Matt Dababneh sexual misconduct allegations====\nIn December 2017, eight former aides to Sherman said that his offices in Washington, D.C. and California had a toxic environment characterized by frequent \"verbal abuse from the congressman and senior staff that made them feel bullied and demoralized.\"<ref name=\"Cadei\">Emily Cadei, [http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/congress/article190444319.html Fear and yelling in L.A. congressman\u2019s office led to silence on harassment, aides say], McClatchy DC (December 19, 201).</ref> A focus of the criticism was [[Matt Dababneh]], Sherman's district director and a close advisor,<ref name=\"Cadei\"/> who began working for Sherman in 2005, and became district director to Sherman in 2009.<ref name=\"Mason\">Melanie Mason, [http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-pol-ca-matt-dababneh-harassment-20171204-story.html California assemblyman accused of forcing lobbyist into bathroom and masturbating], ''Los Angeles Times'' (December 4, 2017).</ref> Dababneh was elected to the [[California State Assembly]] in 2013,<ref name=\"Mason\"/> and resigning from that body after allegations of sexual assault and other misconduct were made against him.<ref name=\"Cadei\"/> Former employees in Sherman's office told the ''Los Angeles Times'' that Dababneh frequently made inappropriate sexual remarks, including degrading and sexist comments, and bragged about his sexual exploits.<ref name=\"Cadei\"/> No one suggested that Sherman knew of Dababneh's conduct, but several staffers said that the office environment did not encourage reporting and said that Sherman would not have been receptive to complaints about a trusted advisor.<ref name=\"Cadei\"/>\n\nSherman has acknowledged being \"a demanding boss\" but \"denied that his management style contributed to the silence about Dababneh's behavior.\"<ref name=\"Cadei\"/> Surveys of Capitol Hill staff rated Sherman as one of the more difficult members to work for, with high staff turnover rates.<ref name=\"Cadei\"/>\n\nIn January 2018, Sherman held a town hall meeting in [[Reseda, California|Reseda]], where a questioner who supported a Democratic primary challenged to Sherman accused the congressman of having an inadequate sexual harassment policy. Sherman replied that \"We have five different ways to report sexual harassment in my office. One among those is to talk to me personally. And I talk to each staff member several times a year about the office policy.\" The exchange was cut from a video of the event that Sherman's office posted to YouTube; the office said that it excluded from the highlight reel \"all questions asked by a questioner working with an opponent\u2019s campaign if the questioner failed to disclose that fact in their question.\"<ref>Emily Cadei, [http://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article198996769.html Congressman\u2019s office deletes question on sexual harassment scandal from town hall video], McClatchy DC (February 8, 2018).</ref>\n\n==== Impeachment ====\nOn July 12, 2017, Sherman introduced an Article of Impeachment (H. Res. 438) against President Donald J. Trump for High Crimes and Misdemeanors.on the grounds that Trump attempted to obstruct justice by firing James Comey from the F.B.I.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-resolution/438|title=H.Res.438 - 115th Congress (2017-2018): Impeaching Donald John Trump, President of the United States, for high crimes and misdemeanors.|first=Sherman,|last=Brad|date=12 July 2017|website=www.congress.gov}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/politics/ct-democrat-impeachment-trump-20170712-story.html|title=House Democrat files first articles of impeachment against President Trump|first=Mike|last=Debonis|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/essential/la-pol-ca-essential-politics-updates-rep-brad-sherman-just-introduced-1499883664-htmlstory.html|title=Rep. Brad Sherman introduces articles of impeachment against Trump|first=Christine|last=Mai-Duc|website=latimes.com}}</ref> Sherman had only one co-sponsor, Al Green (D-TX), who first called for Trump\u2019s impeachment in May 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sherman.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/congressman-sherman-introduces-article-of-impeachment-obstruction-of|title=Congressman Sherman Introduces Article of Impeachment: Obstruction of Justice|date=2017-07-12|work=Congressman Brad Sherman|access-date=2018-08-02|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* [[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Committee on Financial Services]]\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Capital Markets, Insurance, and Government-Sponsored Enterprises|Subcommittee on Capital Markets, Insurance, and Government-Sponsored Enterprises]]\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Insurance, Housing and Community Opportunity|Subcommittee on Insurance, Housing and Community Opportunity]]\n* [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Terrorism, Nonproliferation, and Trade|Subcommittee on Terrorism, Nonproliferation and Trade]] (Ranking Member)\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Asia and the Pacific|Subcommittee on Asia and the Pacific]] (Ranking Member)\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[House Baltic Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://housebalticcaucus.webs.com/members|format=|publisher=House Baltic Caucus|date=|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[Congressional Arts Caucus]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|date=|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://capac-chu.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus|date=|accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== 30th Congressional District ==\nThe 30th congressional district boundaries currently include the communities of:\n\n* [[Bell Canyon, California|Bell Canyon]]\n* [[Canoga Park, Los Angeles]]\n* [[Chatsworth, Los Angeles]]\n* [[Encino, Los Angeles]]\n* [[Granada Hills, Los Angeles]]\n* [[Hidden Hills, California|Hidden Hills]]\n* [[Northridge, Los Angeles]]\n* [[Porter Ranch, Los Angeles]]\n* [[Reseda, Los Angeles]]\n* [[Santa Susana Field Laboratory]]\n* [[Sherman Oaks, Los Angeles]]\n* [[Studio City, Los Angeles]]\n* [[Tarzana, Los Angeles]]\n* [[Toluca Lake, Los Angeles]]\n* [[West Hills, Los Angeles]]\n* [[Winnetka, Los Angeles]]\n* [[Woodland Hills, Los Angeles]]\n\n==Personal life==\n\nOn December 3, 2006, Sherman married Lisa Nicola Kaplan, a foreign affairs officer for the [[United States Department of State|U.S. State Department]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/03/fashion/weddings/03Kaplan.html?ref=weddings |title=Lisa Kaplan and Brad Sherman |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=December 3, 2006}}</ref> The couple\u2019s first child, Molly Hannah Sherman, was born on January 14, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|last=Oczypok |first=Kate |url=http://thehill.com/capital-living/announcements/25098-announcements-january-20-2009 |title=Announcements \u2013 January 20, 2009 |publisher=The Hill |date= |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> Their\nsecond child, Naomi Claire Sherman, was born on February 6, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wilkie |first=Christina |url=http://thehill.com/capital-living/in-the-know/80293-rep-brad-sherman-welcomes-baby-girl-who-had-good-timing |title=Rep. Brad Sherman welcomes baby girl who had good timing |publisher=The Hill |date=February 8, 2010 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>  Their third child, Lucy Rayna Sherman, was born on August 8, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|last=Felde |first=Kitty |url=http://www.scpr.org/blogs/kitty-felde/2011/08/09/another-sherman-sherman-oaks/ |title=Another Sherman in Sherman Oaks |publisher=KPCC |date=August 9, 2011 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Jewish members of the United States Congress]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource author}}\n* [http://bradsherman.house.gov/ Congressman Brad Sherman] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.bradsherman.com/ Brad Sherman for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/California/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Brad_Sherman_%5BD-30%5D|Brad Sherman}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=s000344 | votesmart=142 | fec=H6CA24113 | congress=brad-sherman/1526 }}<!-- Links formerly displayed via the {{CongLinks}} template:\n* [http://ballotpedia.org/Brad_Sherman Biography] at [[Ballotpedia]]\n* [http://www.nndb.com/people/318/000040198 Biography] at [[NNDB]]\n* [http://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/400371 Congressional profile] at [[GovTrack]]\n* [http://www.opencongress.org/people/show/400371 Congressional profile] at [[Participatory Politics Foundation|OpenCongress]]\n* [http://www.rollcall.com/members/51.html Congressional profile] at ''[[Roll Call]]''\n* [http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00006897 Financial information (federal office)] at [[Center for Responsive Politics|OpenSecrets.org]]\n* [https://apps.washingtonpost.com/politics/capitol-assets/member/brad-sherman Financial investments (personal)] at ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n* [http://www.legistorm.com/member/475/Rep_Brad_Sherman.html Staff salaries, trips and personal finance] at LegiStorm.com\n* [http://www.ontheissues.org/CA/Brad_Sherman.htm Issue positions and quotes] at [[On the Issues]]\n* [http://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n2004-64482 Works by or about Brad Sherman] in libraries ([[WorldCat]] catalog)\n* [http://www.c-spanvideo.org/bradsherman Appearances] on [[C-SPAN]] programs\n* [http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2214316 Appearances] at the [[Internet Movie Database]]\n* [http://topics.blo